So it is now confirmed: $TSLA has been including used cars in its "delivery" reports each quarter for years. The numbers are not new vehicle sales. It's not even clear what they are because the definition keeps on changing, and $TSLA has never defined it. https://t.co/iQ2sES5UZV

Here's what some of those JIRA tickets look like when it comes to "deliveries." And $TSLA has over 150 categories of matters to track within JIRA with approximately tens of thousands of tickets. https://t.co/HsF8rqqvt2

How do we know? $TSLA revolves around a product called JIRA, a bug database commonly used at software companies. At Tesla, JIRA tracks more than just softwareâ€”it tracks *everything*. Weird A/C smell? JIRA ticket. Console glitch? JIRA ticket. Car catch on fire? JIRA ticket.

The auditors at PwC have been looking at something completely different, meanwhile: scanned paper of signatures from actual drop-offs of cars. The customer has to sign something, right? So that's what gets audited while $TSLA plays database games.

In about 2017, $TSLA introduced the "Delivery Count Type," a new way to store information about whether vehicles have been delivered. There are two options: New and Used. But since it's a manual setting, used cars can be "delivered" as "New."

Have they really done that? Oh yes. https://t.co/0d8CGF82Q6

It gets worse. $TSLA's systems are a mess. They have duplicate ways of storing information, some algorithmic (2 + 2 = 4) and others manual (write down "4"). So, for example, there might be an "Is Delivered" column and an "Is Delivered?" column. For real. But there's more. https://t.co/6cgZglZEVC
